<p>While parameter 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf101">
   <mi>N</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> in the TW models summarized above is a fixed population size, the corresponding entity in our SIR model is the fluctuating pathogen population size 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf102">
   <msub>
    <mi>N</mi>
    <mi>p</mi>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> which is related to the (fixed) host population size 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf103">
   <msub>
    <mi>N</mi>
    <mi>h</mi>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> by 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf104">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>N</mi>
     <mi>p</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>N</mi>
      <mi>h</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>⁢</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>I</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>t</mi>
       <mo>⁢</mo>
       <mi>o</mi>
       <mo>⁢</mo>
       <mi>t</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. The average 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf105">
   <msub>
    <mi>I</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mi>t</mi>
     <mo>⁢</mo>
     <mi>o</mi>
     <mo>⁢</mo>
     <mi>t</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> depends on other parameters of the model, scaling in particular with 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf106">
   <mrow>
    <mover accent="true">
     <mi>I</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">¯</mo>
    </mover>
    <mo>∼</mo>
    <msup>
     <mi>s</mi>
     <mn>2</mn>
    </msup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. Hence, it will be convenient for us to use 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf107">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>N</mi>
     <mi>h</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>⁢</mo>
    <msup>
     <mi>s</mi>
     <mn>2</mn>
    </msup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> as one of the relevant ‘control parameters’, replacing 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf108">
   <mi>N</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> of the standard TW model.
</p>
